@government
go-to: menu

The Republic of Turkey, established in October 29th, 1923, is a unitary parliamentary republic, founded after the abolition of the Ottoman Empire and the Turkish War of Independence by the Provisional Government of Ankara, which was under the leadership of Mustafa Kemal Ataturk, who would then be elected as its first president and proclaimed as its founding father by the newly formed parliament.

The Parliament, called “The Grand National Assembly” formally, is elected based on a proportional representation system, giving parties seats roughly proportional to their vote share in each electoral district. Traditionally, the presidency has been mostly a ceremonial position, with real executive authority being exercised by the prime minister of Turkey. Usually, the President is elected from one of the many members of the parliament, and after the coup in 1960, is expected to sever all prior connections to any political parties existing. A majority vote-of-no-confidence can remove the current government.

In the election to be held by the parliament, the candidate who receives the absolute majority of the valid votes is elected president. If that candidate fails to receive the majority of the valid votes in the election, the presidential election will be scheduled to be renewed. The president is elected for a term of office of five years and is eligible for one re-election (before 1961 however, there were no limits for presidency). To serve as president, one must fulfill three requirements; being a Turkish citizen with eligibility, being at least 40 years old, and having completed a higher education. The president is the commander-in-chief of the Turkish military,  heads the National Security Council, and all presidential decrees, except those which the president is empowered to enact on his own, has to be signed by the prime minister and the minister concerned, in accordance with the provisions of the constitution and other laws.

Turkey is divided geographichally and politically into seven different regions, each of which have their own unique culture and and socioeconomic differences. Officially a secular state, Turkey has a Muslim-majority population. Turkey is home to over 60 million people; most are ethnic Turks, while Kurds are the largest ethnic minority.

@weimar_timeline
go-to: menu

= Timeline of the Republic of Turkey (until 1989)

**1923**: The Republic of Turkey is declared after the abolition of the Ottoman Sultanate by Mustafa Kemal Pasha and the Grand National Assembly. Mustafa Kemal is elected unanimously as the first president of the Republic. The existing delegates of the parliament are included and have formed the Republican People’s Party (CHP), which would continue to be the sole ruling party of the Republic for more than two decades.

**1930**: Following the Great Depression and the burden of taxation and changing socioeconomic taxations, Mustafa Kemal issues the formation of a new opposition party, the Liberal Republican Party (SCF) in order to give the citizenry a voice in the parliament and gradually start the transformation of the republic into a multi-party democracy. After 6 months, the party abolishes itself, citing reasons such as bullying from CHP members and events of unrest such as Menemen case. The republic would remain a one-party state until after the WW2.

**1939**: After almost one year following the death of Mustafa Kemal (given surname Ataturk, meaning Father of the Turks), World War 2 breaks. The republic would remain neutral until almost one month before the end of war. Ismet Inonu, close confidant and right hand man of Ataturk, would lead the party and the state as “National Chief”, imposing strict economical and social control mechanisms during the years of war. Unrest and discontent brews towards the CHP dominance.

**1946**: Following the end of war, Turkey ends up on the Allied side, and Inonu, hoping to secure Allied relations and realize the Kemalist vision of a multi-party democracy, paves the path of a new party to be formed in the parliament. Democrat Party, led by Celal Bayar,his long-time rival and a proponent of laissez-faire economy, and the energetic firebrand landowner Adnan Menderes, is forced to enter the first multi-party elections in Turkey. Due to a lack of party infrastructure and member organization, along with allegations of electoral fraud commited by CHP, they lose in a landslide.

**1950**: Having reorganized the party and prepared diligenty, Democrat Party (DP) makes an astounding comeback and wins the general elections in a landslide, which won 416 of the 487 seats with 55% of the vote. Celal Bayar is elected president, while Adnan Menderes takes the helm as the prime minister. For the first time since its inception, CHP is relegated to an opposition party. Inonu quietly acquiesces to the results, and accepts his role as the main opposition leader.

**1960**: The Coup d’Etat of 1960; after a decade of gradually rising autocratic tendencies, weakening economy and general unrest towards the possibility of an islamic transformation, an attempt by Kemalist and reactionary officers within the military (including both right and left wing officers) to take power and restore democratic processes, is launched. Adnan Menderes, alongside two of his ministers, is executed following a year of trials by the Supreme Court. DP is shut down, and one year later, a new constitution is drawn up after a successful referendum, called by many as heretofore “the most libertarian constitution of the republic”. Cemal Gürsel, the de-jure leader of the junta, is elected president.

**1971**: Military Memorandum of March 12th; following a decade of political violence, instability and social unrest, along with economic instability, the Chief of Staff of the Armed Forces, Memduh Tağmaç, issues an ultimatum to the prime minister Süleyman Demirel, leader of the Justice Party (AP) who himself was raised in grassroots of DP. Following the ultimatum, Demirel resigned, while Inonu, still as the leader of CHP, denounced the intervention of the military. Public prosecutions towards left wing organizatons such as the Worker’s Party of Turkey (TİP) and Turkish People’s Liberation Army (THKP-C), along many others, are issued. Nihat Erim, a party technocrat and prominent member of the Orthodox Kemalist wing of CHP, is accepted as the prime minister via general consensus of the parties and the military. Many leading figures of the leftist movement would be executed or silenced in the upcoming months. Almost a year later, Inonu himself would lose the party leadership to Bulent Ecevit, prominent member of the more center-left wing of the party, who would pivot the party’s ideology towards what would later be called “Left Kemalism”

**1974**: The Military Intervention/Invasion of Cyprus: Following a background of bilateral political violence between the Turkish and the Greek constituents of Cyprus, and in response to a Greek junta sponsored coup d’etat, CHP and Ecevit, having won the general elections a year prior and leading the ruling coalition alongside the islamic conservative National Salvation Party (MSP), launches an intervention force to the island, to protect the interests of the islands’ citizens, and restore order. As a result, the island would be separated into two entities following a ceasefire, the “southern” Cyprus, recognized as the legitimate government of the island, and the “northern” one, considered illegitimate by most of the world, resulting in what would later be called as the “Cyprus Issue”.

**1977**: Bloody May Day of 1977; a part of the wave of political violence in Turkey during the 70’s; where unknown assailants and perpetrators would open fire towards the leftist demostrators numbering 500.000, resulting in the death of almost 50 people, and 200 or so injured. None of the perpetrators would ever be caught or identified, who were thought to be right-wing paramilitaries or even agents of CIA or Operation Gladio, a clandestine operation aiming at elimination of  communist or leftist organizations in order to halt the creeping expansion of the USSR.

**1980**: The Coup d’Etat of 1980; following the zenith of political violence, electoral and parliamentary gridlock of the election of a new president, and discontent in the military, the Chief of Staff Kenan Evren, with coordination from all parts of the military, launches the coup on September 12th. Swathes of both right and left wing paramilitaries, political activists and even ordinary citizenry are arrested, trialed, executed and tortured. All parliamentary activities would be suspended, and every political party, including CHP, would be shut down, with their leaders sentenced to prison and banned from political activities. Kenan Evren, the head of the junta, is elected president following an overwhelming majority, and a new constitution drafted in the following year, citing the ’61 constitution as “too libertarian”. Mass persecutions and strict social regulations come into play as the military effectively rules the country.

**1984**:  The formation of the Worker’s Party of Kurdistan (PKK); which has been involved in armed clashes towards the Turkish security forces since 1979. Abdullah Öcalan, who was a prior member of the Revolutionary Youth Federation of Turkey (Dev-Genç), assumes the position of leadership. The country is effectively plunged into what would later be called “the Kurdish Problem”, where armed resurgencies, assasinations by the paramilitaries and public strife is dominant throughout the republic.

**1989**: The presidential election of 1989; where Turgut Özal, the leader and founder of the Motherland Party (ANAP) is elected president with 94% of the votes following Kenan Evren. True Path Party (DYP, an offshoot of the former AP, along with ANAP) and Social Democratic People’s Party (SHP) boycott the elections, citing their successes in the prior municipal elections as the lack of democratic legitimacy of ANAP, which held a numerical majority in the parliament. 

